trust_attributes.Informed Consent: Making sure participants clearly understand and agree to be part of the research
trust_attributes.Ethical Oversight: Getting approval from ethical committees that watch out for participant welfare
trust_attributes.Data Protection and Privacy: Keeping participant information safe and following privacy laws
trust_attributes.Transparency: Openly sharing who funded the research and any potential conflicts of interest
trust_attributes.Honesty and Integrity: Being truthful throughout the research process and not manipulating data
trust_attributes.Authenticity: Representing findings and participant voices truthfully without distortion
trust_attributes.Clear Documentation of Methods: Writing down all research steps so others understand exactly what was done
trust_attributes.Clear Reporting of Results: Sharing all findings completely, including those that don't match expectations
trust_attributes.Auditability and Method Consistency: Conducting research in a way that allows others to check your work
trust_attributes.External Validation: Having qualified outside experts review the research before sharing it widely
trust_attributes.Open Science Practices: Sharing research materials, data, and/or code so others can verify or build on your work
trust_attributes.Thick Description: Providing rich details about the research context so others can judge its applicability
trust_attributes.Research Self Awareness: Recognizing how the researcher's own background and viewpoints might affect the research
trust_attributes.Neutral Analysis Procedures: Using methods that minimize the researcher's personal biases in analyzing results
trust_attributes.Procedural Stability: Following the same research procedures throughout the entire study
trust_attributes.Methodology Selection Rationale: Clearly explaining why specific research methods were chosen
trust_attributes.Fairness to Alternate Views: Giving competing ideas or theories equal consideration and fair treatment
trust_attributes.Coherence of Findings: Making sure conclusions make sense across all your data sources
trust_attributes.Complementary Approaches: Using different methods that work together to create a fuller understanding
trust_attributes.Actionability: Ensuring research results can be used to make real-world improvements
trust_attributes.Inclusiveness of Perspectives: Including diverse viewpoints in the research design and interpretation
trust_attributes.Appropriate Sampling: Selecting participants or data in a way that makes sense for the research questions
trust_attributes.Randomization: Assigning participants to groups by chance to avoid bias
trust_attributes.Internal Validity: Making sure your research design truly supports the cause-and-effect claims you make
trust_attributes.External Validity: The degree to which findings apply to other people, settings, or situations
trust_attributes.Triangulation: Using different data sources or methods to check if they point to the same conclusion
trust_attributes.Member Checking: Asking participants to review findings to confirm they accurately reflect their experiences
trust_attributes.Test-Retest Reliability: Getting similar results when measuring the same thing at different times
trust_attributes.Inter-Rater Reliability: Having different people evaluate the same thing and getting similar results
trust_attributes.Construct Validity: Making sure your measurements actually capture the concepts you claim to measure
trust_attributes.Appropriate Statistical Tests: Using the right statistical methods for your research questions and data
trust_attributes.Reporting of Effect Sizes and Confidence: Clearly showing how strong your findings are and how certain you can be about them
